    plumbingAndWaterPara: "NYC DEP water is hard but chloraminated, which rules out certain carbon filters. Nearly every pre-war building has a supply riser that the plumber will have to chase down to the basement to isolate for shutdown. Master plumbers (required for any permitted work under NYC Admin Code 28-401.3) charge $150-$220/hour versus $95-$130 in suburban Jersey. Gas line work requires a separate LAA plus National Grid or Con Edison gas re-inspection before the meter is restored.",
    layoutConstraintsPara: "Manhattan galleys of 7-8 feet wide force 24-inch appliances and single-row cabinetry with no realistic island option. Outer-borough row-homes in Bay Ridge and Forest Hills allow peninsulas but rarely true islands because the structural spine wall sits center. Brooklyn brownstone parlor-floor kitchens are limited by joist runs that prevent removing the wall between kitchen and rear yard without a licensed-engineer letter filed with DOB.",
    permitTimelinePara: "DOB NOW approval for a kitchen ALT-2 runs 4-8 weeks once plans are stamped. Co-op alteration agreement review adds another 4-6 weeks and the managing agent will stop work until a fresh COI names the building, the managing agent, and the board as additional insureds. Summer work stoppage rules in many pre-war buildings block construction from Memorial Day through Labor Day, which compresses the realistic start window.",
    localDesignerCulturePara: "NYC designer culture clusters around the A&D Building on Third Avenue and the NYDC on Lexington. NKBA-certified kitchen designers in the metro routinely charge $200-$400/hour or 15-20% of total project cost. Christopher Peacock and Clive Christian serve the Park Avenue tier. Mid-market homeowners often use Sweeten or Block Renovation to source vetted contractors because the traditional architect route adds $25,000-$75,000 on modest projects.",
